,'2012-07-21 18:13:46','[b]FAQ[/b]\n\n[b]Uploading[/b]\n\n\nIs everyone allowed to upload? : Hide\nMissing space, maybe make RULES a link? I know its at the top of the page so not necessary but mentioned for completeness.\n\'Loose\', should be \'lose\'.\n\n    [color=#FF0000]Yes,mak[/color]e sure that you have read and understood the RULES first!!\n    Or you might [color=#FF0000]loose [/color]that privilege.\n\n   Correction\n    Yes, make sure that you have read and understood the RULES first!!\n    Or you might lose that privilege.\n\n\nI have a question about uploading? : Hide\n\n    Check the tutorial forum [color=#FF0000]first,then[/color] post in the Help and Support forum.\n\n\nWhen uploading a torrent file I get the message \"Invalid Filename\" : Hide\nsyntax semantics\n\n    Make sure you haven\'t got either a space at the beginning or end of the file name, or are using a special character that cannot be recognized.  Keep the name simple!!  It is also recommended [color=#FF0000]to not[/color] use Internet Explorer when transferring files, and check if there [color=#FF0000]is[/color] any corrupted files within your torrent.  Avoid many directories, keep it simple.\n\n\n  Correction\n    Make sure you haven\'t got either a space at the beginning or end of the file name, or are using a special character that cannot be recognized.  Keep the name simple!!  It is also recommended not to use Internet Explorer when transferring files, and check if there are any corrupted files within your torrent.  Avoid many directories, keep it simple.\n\n\n\nIs there any content thats not allowed to be Uploaded? : Hide\nBorked URL, the \'.\' at the end I assume \n\n    NO Child/Beast/Snuff porn!\n    Keep it legal. If in doubt, don\'t post it.  And check the rules concerning [url=/articles.php?topic=forbidden%20content]Forbidden Content.[/url]\n\n\n\n[color=#0033FF]EDIT: DONE[/color]',86439,'2012-07-22 06:54:42'),(44625,5755,86439,'2012-07-21 18:46:08','[b]FAQ[/b]\n\n\n[b]Stats[/b]\nMissing spaces shown in red, ??missing link???, superfluous \'s\' also in red\n\n\n    The following clients are banned for various reaso[color=#FF0000]ns(ch[/color]eating e.t.c)\n\n\n    A[color=#FF0000]lso,mak[/color]e sure that you check the often updated list of malfunctioning/not supported clients/client versions in the forums.  [color=#FF0000](are there any links for this)[/color]\n\n    \n\n    How[color=#FF0000]ever,eve[/color]n these clients go through updates that creat[color=#FF0000]es bu[/color]gs!\n    So you need to keep up to date with the latest reported client problems and fixes!\n\n\n\n   Corrections, except link\n\n    The following clients are banned for various reasons (cheating e.t.c)\n\n\n\n\n    Also, make sure that you check the often updated list of malfunctioning/not supported clients/client versions in the forums.\n\n    \n\n    However, even these clients go through updates that create bugs!\n    So you need to keep up to date with the latest reported client problems and fixes!\n\n\n\n\nWhy is a torrent I\'m leeching/seeding listed several times in my profile? : Hide\n\'a\' for consonants, \'an\' for vowels. \n\n    If for some reason (e.g. pc crash, or frozen client) your client exits improperly and you restart it, it will have a new peer_id, so it will show as a new torrent.  The old one will never rec[color=#FF0000]eive a \"eve[/color]nt=completed\" or \"event=stopped\" and will be listed until some tracker timeout. Just ignore it, it will eventually go away.\n\n\n  Correction\n    If for some reason (e.g. pc crash, or frozen client) your client exits improperly and you restart it, it will have a new peer_id, so it will show as a new torrent.  The old one will never receive an \"event=completed\" or \"event=stopped\" and will be listed until some tracker timeout. Just ignore it, it will eventually go away.\n\n\n\n\nI\'ve finished or cancelled a torrent. Why is it still listed in my profile? : Hide\nSyntax in red.\n\n    Some clients, notably TorrentStorm and Nova Torrent, do not report properly to the tracker when canceling or finishing a torrent. In that case the tracker will keep waiting for some message - and [color=#FF0000]thus listing[/color] the torrent as seeding or leeching - until some timeout occurs. Just ignore it, it will eventually go away.\n\n\n   Correction\n    Some clients, notably TorrentStorm and Nova Torrent, do not report properly to the tracker when canceling or finishing a torrent. In that case the tracker will keep waiting for some message - and will continue to list the torrent as seeding or leeching - until some timeout occurs. Just ignore it, it will eventually go away.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n[color=#0033FF]EDIT: DONE[/color]\n\n',86439,'2012-07-22 06:55:38'),(44626,5762,130545,'2012-07-21 19:19:56','Hi, I sent a staff PM and received a reply. After that, I wasn\'t able to reply again because there was no \'submit\' button. There was just a preview button that turned into an \'edit\' button when i clicked it.\r\n\r\nSo basically, I can\'t reply to my Staff PM',NULL,NULL),(44627,5762,129045,'2012-07-21 19:32:51',':hmmm:\r\n\r\nIt\'s probably because I marked it as \"Resolved\", sorry, I just reverted it, please try again.\r\n\r\n[b][i]EDIT:[/i][/b] In case I really broke it, please report another post of yours, so we can start the process from zero.',129045,'2012-07-21 20:41:28'),(44628,5755,86439,'2012-07-21 20:22:31','[b]Downloading[/b]\n\n\nHow can I improve my download speed? : Hide\n[color=#0000FF]Spaces req\'d after numbers. ie: 1. Do not immediately...\n??? Missing LINK ???\n#4 Additive should be replaced with cumulative\n#6 \'change\', should be \'chance\'[/color]\n\n   [color=#FF0000] 1.Do [/color]not immediately jump on new torrents.  Wait until the seeder/leecher ratio improves a bit.\n\n    2.Make yourself connectable  [color=#FF0000](LINK)[/color]\n    Many have connectability issues that affects their upload/download speed and stats.\n\n\n    4.Limit the number of simultaneous connections\n    Some operating systems (like Windows 9x) do not deal well with a large number of connections, and may even crash. Also some home routers (particularly when running NAT and/or firewall with stateful inspection services) tend to become slow or crash when having to deal with too many connections. There are no fixed values for this, you may try 60 or 100 and experiment with the value. Note that these numbers are [color=#FF0000]additive[/color], if you have two instances of a client running the numbers add up.\n\n\n    6.Just give it some time\n    As explained above peers favour other peers that upload to them. When you start leeching a new torrent you have nothing to offer to other peers and they will tend to ignore you. This makes the starts slow, in particular if, by [color=#FF0000]change[/color], the peers you are connected to include few or no seeders. The download speed should increase as soon as you have some pieces to share.\n\n\n\n\nWhy can\'t I connect? Is the site blocking me? : Hide\n[color=#0000FF]Syntax, reverse the words \'has\' and \'obviously\'[/color]\n    \n    This means that other peers in the swarm will be unable to connect to you, only you to them. Even worse, if two peers are both in this state they will not be able to connect at all. This [color=#FF0000]has obviously[/color] a detrimental effect on the overall speed.\n\n\n\n\nMy ISP uses a transparent proxy. What should I do? : Hide\n[color=#0000FF]This This or This are not links as implied.[/color]\n\n\n    Otherwise you may try the following:\n\n    Choose any public non-anonymous proxy that does not use port 80 (e.g. from [color=#FF0000]this, this or this list[/color]).\n\n\n\n\nWhy can\'t I connect? Is the site blocking me? : Hide\n[color=#0000FF]Mixed use of Caps and LC lettering.\nSome syntax[/color]\n\n\n    Why does it matter?\n\n    Well, [color=#FF0000]M[/color]any private trackers restrict people who aren\'t connectable, [color=#FF0000]and even on some sites no seed bonuses are credited to people who aren\'t[/color]. [color=#FF0000]mo[/color]st importantly people who aren\'t connectable hurt the swarm. Each peer that isn\'t connectable is limited to sharing with only peers who are connectable. If the number of peers who aren\'t connectable is low the result is unnoticeable, [color=#FF0000]Bu[/color]t the higher the percentage goes the slower the swarm becomes until it dies at the point when all peers are unconnectable. There\'s no one left to connect to.\n\n  Corrected\n    Well, many private trackers restrict people who aren\'t connectable, and on some sites no seed bonuses are credited to people who aren\'t. Most importantly people who aren\'t connectable hurt the swarm. Each peer that isn\'t connectable is limited to sharing with only peers who are connectable. If the number of peers who aren\'t connectable is low the result is unnoticeable, but the higher the percentage goes the slower the swarm becomes until it dies at the point when all peers are unconnectable. There\'s no one left to connect to.\n\n\n\nWhy am I unconnectable? Well maybe...\n[color=#0000FF]Spaces after \'-\', all of them\n??Link to port forward thread, tute or .com??[/color]\n\n\n-Lack of proper port forwarding.\n-TURN OFF DHT, PEER EXCHANGE, LOCAL PEER DISCOVERY\n...\n\n\n\n\nWhat can I do about it?\n[color=#0000FF]Lack of caps\nin correct their, should be they\'re\nSeveral spaces missing\nUnnecessary space between Azureus and uTorrent\nYour should be you\'re\n[/color]\n\nSometimes nothing. [color=#FF0000]for[/color] instance if your ISP has you behind a proxy server that blocks incoming requests. If [color=#FF0000]their[/color] only blocking certain ports you can change the port you use, and if [color=#FF0000]their [/color]throttling (this has nothing to do with becoming connectable.) you could use [color=#FF0000]uTorrent or\nAzureus[/color] and enable encryption. It may be that you are trying to torrent from a place of business with routers, proxy servers, firewalls, and/or traffic shaping software, or appliances like websense. If [color=#FF0000]your [/color]even lucky enough to get a torrent running at all, but being connectable is out of the ques[color=#FF0000]tion.Howe[/color]ver, most cases being connectable is fun, easy and can be done without spending any money at all.\n\n[color=#0000FF]Correction[/color]\nSometimes nothing. For instance if your ISP has you behind a proxy server that blocks incoming requests. If they\'re only blocking certain ports you can change the port you use, and if they\'re throttling (this has nothing to do with becoming connectable.) you could use uTorrent or Azureus and enable encryption. It may be that you are trying to torrent from a place of business with routers, proxy servers, firewalls, and/or traffic shaping software, or appliances like websense. If you\'re even lucky enough to get a torrent running at all, but being connectable is out of the question. However, most cases being connectable is fun, easy and can be done without spending any money at all.\n\n\n[color=#0000FF]\nUse of Caps in \'Dont\'[/color]\nFourth, [color=#FF0000]Don[/color]\'t shutdown or start your software with a lot of torrents running. whats a lot? I think 3 would be OK, but 10 is out. The point is shut down and start your torrents individually or groups of 2 or 3 with a pause between, and if you shutdown your computer wait for your start up programs to finish before starting your torrents back up.\n\n[color=#0000FF]Correction[/color]\nFourth, don\'t shutdown or start your software with a lot of torrents running. whats a lot? I think 3 would be OK, but 10 is out. The point is shut down and start your torrents individually or groups of 2 or 3 with a pause between, and if you shutdown your computer wait for your start up programs to finish before starting your torrents back up.\n\n[color=#0000FF]\nUse of LC in \'defaults\'\nYou\'re, not your\nAdded \'as\' between \'up\' and \'connectable\'[/color]\nFifth, limit the number of connections per torrent and total connectio[color=#FF0000]ns. de[/color]faults will usually work but maybe shrink it down more if [color=#FF0000]your[/color] still showing [color=#FF0000]up unconnectable[/color].\n\n[color=#0000FF]Correction[/color]\nFifth, limit the number of connections per torrent and total connections. Defaults will usually work but maybe shrink it down more if you\'re still showing up as unconnectable.\n\n\n\n[color=#0000FF]\nUse of UC in \'Your\'\nprotocols is spelled wrong\nMissing \'t; in bittorrent\n[/color]\nSeventh, [color=#FF0000]Your[/color] router may just not be good at handling P2P [color=#FF0000]protocalls [/color]like [color=#FF0000]bitorrent[/color] which require many connections made over a short time. \n\n[color=#0000FF]Correction[/color]\nSeventh, Your router may just not be good at handling P2P protocols like bittorrent which require many connections made over a short time. \n\n\n\n[color=#0000FF]\nUse of UC in \'Try\'\n[/color]\nEigh[color=#FF0000]th, Try[/color] using ports between 65,000 and 65,500 this works better for most people, and do not use software like PeerGuardian2. TURN OFF DHT, PEER EXCHANGE, and LOCAL PEER DISCOVERY\n\n[color=#0000FF]Correction[/color]\nEighth, try using ports between 65,000 and 65,500 this works better for most people, and do not use software like PeerGuardian2. TURN OFF DHT, PEER EXCHANGE, and LOCAL PEER DISCOVERY\n\n\n\n[color=#0000FF]\nMissing space between forwarding. Port Forwarding\nShould Portfroward.com be a LINK?\n[/color]\nFinally, and this can be the hardest part for most people, follow one of many very good guides concerning port forwar[color=#FF0000]ding.Por[/color]t Forwarding Guides Listed by Manufacturer and Model - PortForward.com is a good place to start.\n\n[color=#0000FF]Correction[/color]\nFinally, and this can be the hardest part for most people, follow one of many very good guides concerning port forwarding. Port Forwarding Guides Listed by Manufacturer and Model - PortForward.com is a good place to start.\n\n\n\n\ncont...\n\n\n\n\n[color=#0033FF]EDIT: DONE[/color]\n',86439,'2012-07-22 06:56:58'),(44629,5755,129045,'2012-07-21 20:26:17','That\'s some dedication :gjob:\n\nI\'m rather useless at this, so I\'ll only look for easy ones :P\n\n- On http://empornium.mooo.com/articles.php?topic=requests\n\nRemains from What.CD:\n[quote][*] [b]Do not unfill requests for trivial reasons[/b]. If you did not specify in your request what you wanted [color=#FF0000](such as bitrates or a particular edition), do not unfill and later change the description. Do not unfill requests if you are unsure of what you are doing (e.g. the filled torrent may be a transcode, but you don\'t know how to tell). Ask for help from staff in that case.[/color] You may unfill if the torrent doesn\'t fit your specifications stated clearly in the request.[/quote] [color=red]Fixed - Clownius[/color]\n\n- On http://empornium.mooo.com/articles.php?topic=clients\n\nDoesn\'t really list any clients, be it allowed, recommended or banned. Similar information available in the FAQ. [color=red] Awaiting a whitelist to be created cant fix right now - Clownius[/color]\n\n- On http://empornium.mooo.com/articles.php?topic=upload\n\nSmall inconsistency:\n[quote]-If you post a siterip/[color=#FF0000]mega-pak[/color]...\n...\nPosting a [color=#0000FF]megapack[/color]...\n[/quote]\n\n- On http://empornium.mooo.com/articles.php?topic=uploadchecklist\nThere could be a link to http://empornium.mooo.com/articles.php?topic=presentation and vice versa :hmmm:\n\nAs for the tutorials:\n\n- A similar \'dummy\' guide for the other recommended clients would be nice. (Vuze\\Azureus and rtorrent)',47234,'2012-07-22 10:22:56'),(44631,5755,86439,'2012-07-21 21:18:36','[color=#0000FF]Again, should PortForward.com, at least in the top of this section, be a LINK.[/color]\n\nFinally, and this can be the hardest part for most people, follow one of many very good guides concerning port forwarding.Port Forwarding Guides Listed by Manufacturer and Model - [color=#FF0000]PortForward.com[/color] is a good place to start.\n\n[color=#0000FF]superfluous line break[/color]\n2. Next you need to setup your router to forward the correct ports to your computer. A step by step guide for just about every router is located at PortForward\'s Other Guides - PortForward.com , scroll down and select port forwarding guides by router. Just select your router, a[color=#FF0000]nd\nthen[/color] click on your bit-torrent client for specific steps on how to correctly configure your setup. Remember to use the IP address you assigned your computer in step one. Also, the port number can be almost anything you want, but I suggest using something over 50,000.\n\n[color=#0000FF]Correction[/color]\n2. Next you need to setup your router to forward the correct ports to your computer. A step by step guide for just about every router is located at PortForward\'s Other Guides - PortForward.com , scroll down and select port forwarding guides by router. Just select your router, and then click on your bit-torrent client for specific steps on how to correctly configure your setup. Remember to use the IP address you assigned your computer in step one. Also, the port number can be almost anything you want, but I suggest using something over 50,000.\n\n\n[color=#0000FF]LC lettering[/color]\n3. If you run a firewall you\'ll need to set it up to allow the correct tra[color=#FF0000]ffic. go [/color]to Port Forwarding Guides Listed by Manufacturer and Model - PortForward.com select the firewall you have and follow the steps.\n\n[color=#0000FF]Correction[/color]\n3. If you run a firewall you\'ll need to set it up to allow the correct traffic. Go to Port Forwarding Guides Listed by Manufacturer and Model - PortForward.com select the firewall you have and follow the steps.\n\n\n\n[color=#0000FF]Line break    LC/UC    missing \'and\'    missing space    Open port check tool, should be a link?\n[/color]\n4. Once you\'ve set up all of that, make sure your client is running, then go to Open Port Check [color=#FF0000]Tool\nenter[/color] in the port you\'re [color=#FF0000]using.This[/color] page will tell you whether your port is open, stealthed, or [color=#FF0000]closed.If[/color] it is open, then you should be Connectable.\n\n[color=#0000FF]Correction[/color]\n4. Once you\'ve set up all of that, make sure your client is running, then go to Open Port Check Tool and enter in the port you\'re using. This page will tell you whether your port is open, stealthed, or closed. If it is open, then you should be Connectable.\n\n\n\nWhy have your computer set to a static IP?\n[color=#0000FF]Spaces    line break   [/color]\n\nOn networks where DCHP (Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol) is running you get an IP address issued automatically when you [color=#FF0000]connect.In[/color] theory this is great but until you connect you donâ€™t know what this IP address will be. Most routers have a set range of IP addresses to [color=#FF0000]use\nbut[/color] how these are issued depends on the make/model of the [color=#FF0000]router.So[/color] if you set up port forwarding for the IP currently issued to your PC today, will it work tomorrow or even after a reboot? Maybe but if the PC gets issued a different IP address your PC will never see the data on the ports you [color=#FF0000]forwarded.How[/color] can you be sure of always having the port forwarded to the right computer port â€“ simple set up a static IP address. That way every [color=#FF0000]timethe[/color] computer restarts it will be the same IP address and the port forwarding will work perfectly.\n\n\n[color=#0000FF]Correction[/color]\nOn networks where DCHP (Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol) is running you get an IP address issued automatically when you connect. In theory this is great but until you connect you donâ€™t know what this IP address will be. Most routers have a set range of IP addresses to use but how these are issued depends on the make/model of the router. So if you set up port forwarding for the IP currently issued to your PC today, will it work tomorrow or even after a reboot? Maybe but if the PC gets issued a different IP address your PC will never see the data on the ports you forwarded. How can you be sure of always having the port forwarded to the right computer port â€“ simple set up a static IP address. That way every time the computer restarts it will be the same IP address and the port forwarding will work perfectly.\n\n\nAlternate port (81)\n[color=#0000FF]the way the swap is described, swaps which should be swapped with which. 81 in, 80 out, but it says 81 out, 80 in.\n[/color]\n\nSome of our torrents use ports other than the usual HTTP port 80. This may cause problems for some users, for instance those behind some firewall or proxy configurations. You can easily solve this by editing the .torrent file yourself with any torrent editor, e.g. MakeTorrent, and [color=#FF0000]replacing the announce url http://torrents.empornium.me:81 with torrents.empornium.me:80[/color] or just torrents.empornium.me.\n\n[color=#0000FF]Correction[/color]\nSome of our torrents use ports other than the usual HTTP port 80. This may cause problems for some users, for instance those behind some firewall or proxy configurations. You can easily solve this by editing the .torrent file yourself with any torrent editor, e.g. MakeTorrent, and replacing the announce url http://torrents.empornium.me:80 with torrents.empornium.me:81 or just torrents.empornium.me.\n\n\n\n\n[color=#0033FF]EDIT: DONE[/color]\n',86439,'2012-07-22 06:58:19'),(44632,5755,86439,'2012-07-21 21:52:56','Troubleshooting your connection. : Hide\n\nFor Windows:\n[color=#0000FF]Might be wise to mention that stupid space between \'ipconfig\' and the \'/\'\nAnd the Mac one, not sure if that space (before the dash) is intentional or not.[/color]\n\n   ... type ipco[color=#FF0000]nfig /rel[/color]ease and press Enter\n   ... type ipco[color=#FF0000]nfig /rene[/color]w and press Enter\n\n   \n\n  If using Mac OS X 10.5.8 or 10.6.x, type [color=#FF0000]dscacheutil -flushcache[/color]\n\n\n\n3. Check that there are no issues with the tracker\n[color=#0000FF]\'There\' if referring to elsewhere than where they are.[/color]\n\nCheck the forums, if there are any known issues with the tracker, you can often find more information [color=#FF0000]here[/color]\n\n[color=#0000FF]Correction[/color]\nCheck the forums, if there are any known issues with the tracker, you can often find more information there.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n[color=#009966]LOL! This next show/hide option is hidden in the last show/hide option, its not on the main page[/color] Missing [ /  spioler   ]\nWhat if I can\'t find the answer to my problem here? : Hide\n[color=#0000FF]syntax[/color]\n\n\n    The [color=#FF0000]more you tell[/color] the [color=#FF0000]easiest[/color] it will be for us, and the more probable your post will get a reply.  And needless to say: be polite. Demanding help rarely works, asking for it usually does the trick.\n\n   [color=#0000FF]correction[/color]\n    The more information you provide the easier it will be for us, and the more probable your post will get a reply.  And needless to say: be polite. Demanding help rarely works, asking for it usually does the trick.\n\n\n\n[color=#0000FF]spaces   capitalised \'I\'[/color]\n    Links:\n\n    I have a suggest[color=#FF0000]ion-whe[/color]re do i put it?\n    In the - Suggestion forum.  Be polite.\n\n    I couldnt find the answer to my question here.\n    Use the - Help and Support Forum -make sure your question hasn\'t been asked there before.\n\n\n[color=#0000FF]correction[/color]\n    Links:\n\n    I have a suggestion - where do I put it?\n    In the - Suggestion forum.  Be polite.\n\n    I couldnt find the answer to my question here.\n    Use the - Help and Support Forum - make sure your question hasn\'t been asked there before.\n\n\n\n[color=#0033FF]EDIT: DONE[/color]',86439,'2012-07-22 06:59:23'),(44634,5763,85636,'2012-07-21 21:55:56','[size=3][b][color=#FF0000]Moved as is to Help in its own chapter - need to decide if it stays there or goes to staff operator reference - Delete after double check[/color][/b][/size]\n\n\n\nNickServ Commands\n\nNickServ allows you to â€œregisterâ€ a nickname and prevent others from using it. The following commands allow for registration and maintenance of nicknames; to use them, type /msg NickServ command. For more information on a specific command, type /msg NickServ HELP command.\n \n[b]REGISTER[/b]\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ REGISTER password [email]\n \n Registers your nickname in the NickServ database.  Once\n your nick is registered, you can use the SET and ACCESS\n commands to configure your nick\'s settings as you like\n them.  Make sure you remember the password you use when\n registering - you\'ll need it to make changes to your nick\n later.  (Note that case matters!  ANOPE, Anope, and\n anope are all different passwords!)\n \n Guidelines on choosing passwords:\n \n Passwords should not be easily guessable.  For example,\n using your real name as a password is a bad idea.  Using\n your nickname as a password is a much worse idea ;) and,\n in fact, NickServ will not allow it.  Also, short\n passwords are vulnerable to trial-and-error searches, so\n you should choose a password at least 5 characters long.\n Finally, the space character cannot be used in passwords.\n \n The parameter email is optional and will set the email\n for your nick immediately. However, it may be required\n on certain networks.\n Your privacy is respected; this e-mail won\'t be given to\n any third-party person.\n \n This command also creates a new group for your nickname,\n that will allow you to register other nicks later sharing\n the same configuration, the same set of memos and the\n same channel privileges. For more information on this\n feature, type /msg NickServ HELP GROUP.[/quote]\n \n[b]GROUP[/b]\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  GROUP target password\n \n This command makes your nickname join the target nickname\'s\n group. password is the password of the target nickname.\n \n Joining a group will allow you to share your configuration,\n memos, and channel privileges with all the nicknames in the\n group, and much more!\n \n A group exists as long as it is useful. This means that even\n if a nick of the group is dropped, you won\'t lose the\n shared things described above, as long as there is at\n least one nick remaining in the group.\n \n You can use this command even if you have not registered\n your nick yet. If your nick is already registered, you\'ll\n need to identify yourself before using this command. Type\n /msg NickServ HELP IDENTIFY for more information. This\n last may be not possible on your IRC network.\n \n It is recommended to use this command with a non-registered\n nick because it will be registered automatically when\n using this command. You may use it with a registered nick (to\n change your group) only if your network administrators allowed\n it.\n \n You can only be in one group at a time. Group merging is\n not possible.\n \n Note: all the nicknames of a group have the same password.[/quote]\n \n[b]IDENTIFY[/b]\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  IDENTIFY password\n \n Tells NickServ that you are really the owner of this\n nick.  Many commands require you to authenticate yourself\n with this command before you use them.  The password\n should be the same one you sent with the REGISTER\n command.[/quote]\n \n[b]LOGOUT[/b]\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  LOGOUT\n \n This reverses the effect of the IDENTIFY command, i.e.\n make you not recognized as the real owner of the nick\n anymore. Note, however, that you won\'t be asked to reidentify\n yourself.[/quote]\n \n[b]DROP[/b]\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  DROP [nickname]\n \n Drops your nickname from the NickServ database.  A nick\n that has been dropped is free for anyone to re-register.\n \n You may drop a nick within your group by passing it\n as the nick parameter.\n \n In order to use this command, you must first identify\n with your password (/msg NickServ HELP IDENTIFY for more\n information).[/quote]\n \n[b]ACCESS[/b]\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  ACCESS ADD mask\n         ACCESS DEL mask\n         ACCESS LIST\n \n Modifies or displays the access list for your nick.  This\n is the list of addresses which will be automatically\n recognized by NickServ as allowed to use the nick.  If\n you want to use the nick from a different address, you\n need to send an IDENTIFY command to make NickServ\n recognize you.\n \n Examples:\n \n     ACCESS ADD anyone@*.bepeg.com\n         Allows access to user anyone from any machine in\n         the bepeg.com domain.\n \n     ACCESS DEL anyone@*.bepeg.com\n         Reverses the previous command.\n \n     ACCESS LIST\n         Displays the current access list.[/quote]\n\n[b]SET[/b]\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET option parameters\n \n Sets various nickname options.  option can be one of:\n \n     DISPLAY    Set the display of your group in Services\n     PASSWORD   Set your nickname password\n     LANGUAGE   Set the language Services will use when\n                    sending messages to you\n     URL        Associate a URL with your nickname\n     EMAIL      Associate an E-mail address with your nickname\n     ICQ        Associate an ICQ number with your nickname\n     GREET      Associate a greet message with your nickname\n     KILL       Turn protection on or off\n     SECURE     Turn nickname security on or off\n     PRIVATE    Prevent your nickname from appearing in a\n                    /msg NickServ LIST\n     HIDE       Hide certain pieces of nickname information\n     MSG        Change the communication method of Services\n     AUTOOP     Should services op you automatically.\n \n In order to use this command, you must first identify\n with your password (/msg NickServ HELP IDENTIFY for more\n information).\n \n Type /msg NickServ HELP SET option for more information\n on a specific option.[/quote]\n \n[b]SET DISPLAY[/b]\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET DISPLAY new-display\n \n Changes the display used to refer to your nickname group in\n Services. The new display MUST be a nick of your group.[/quote]\n\n[b]SET PASSWORD[/b]\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET PASSWORD new-password\n \n Changes the password used to identify you as the nick\'s\n owner.[/quote]\n\n[b]SET URL[/b]\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET URL url\n \n Associates the given URL with your nickname.  This URL\n will be displayed whenever someone requests information\n on your nick with the INFO command.[/quote]\n \n[b]SET EMAIL[/b]\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET EMAIL address\n \n Associates the given E-mail address with your nickname.\n This address will be displayed whenever someone requests\n information on the nickname with the INFO command.[/quote]\n \n[b]SET HIDE[/b]\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET HIDE {EMAIL | STATUS | USERMASK | QUIT} {ON | OFF}\n \n Allows you to prevent certain pieces of information from\n being displayed when someone does a NickServ INFO on your\n nick.  You can hide your E-mail address (EMAIL), last seen\n user@host mask (USERMASK), your services access status\n (STATUS) and  last quit message (QUIT).\n The second parameter specifies whether the information should\n be displayed (OFF) or hidden (ON).[/quote]\n \n[b]SET ICQ[/b]\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET ICQ number\n \n Associates the given ICQ number with your nickname.  This\n number will be displayed whenever someone requests\n information on your nick with the INFO command.[/quote]\n \n[b]SET GREET[/b]\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET GREET message\n \n Makes the given message the greet of your nickname, that\n will be displayed when joining a channel that has GREET\n option enabled, provided that you have the necessary\n access on it.[/quote]\n\n[b]SET KILL[/b]\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET KILL {ON | QUICK | IMMED | OFF}\n \n Turns the automatic protection option for your nick\n on or off.  With protection on, if another user\n tries to take your nick, they will be given one minute to\n change to another nick, after which NickServ will forcibly change\n their nick.\n \n If you select QUICK, the user will be given only 20 seconds\n to change nicks instead of the usual 60.  If you select\n IMMED, user\'s nick will be changed immediately without being\n warned first or given a chance to change their nick; please\n do not use this option unless necessary.  Also, your\n network\'s administrators may have disabled this option.[/quote]\n\n[b]SET SECURE[/b]\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET SECURE {ON | OFF}\n \n Turns NickServ\'s security features on or off for your\n nick.  With SECURE set, you must enter your password\n before you will be recognized as the owner of the nick,\n regardless of whether your address is on the access\n list.  However, if you are on the access list, NickServ\n will not auto-kill you regardless of the setting of the\n KILL option.[/quote]\n\n[b]SET PRIVATE[/b]\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET PRIVATE {ON | OFF}\n \n Turns NickServ\'s privacy option on or off for your nick.\n With PRIVATE set, your nickname will not appear in\n nickname lists generated with NickServ\'s LIST command.\n (However, anyone who knows your nickname can still get\n information on it using the INFO command.)[/quote]\n\n[b]SET MSG[/b]\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  SET MSG {ON | OFF}\n \n Allows you to choose the way Services are communicating with\n you. With MSG set, Services will use messages, else they\'ll\n use notices.[/quote]\n\n[b]UPDATE[/b]\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  UPDATE\n Updates your current status, i.e. it checks for new memos,\n sets needed chanmodes (ModeonID) and updates your vhost and\n your userflags (lastseentime, etc).[/quote]\n \n[b]RECOVER[/b]\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  RECOVER nickname [password]\n \n Allows you to recover your nickname if someone else has\n taken it; this does the same thing that NickServ does\n automatically if someone tries to use a kill-protected\n nick.\n \n When you give this command, NickServ will bring a fake\n user online with the same nickname as the user you\'re\n trying to recover your nick from.  This causes the IRC\n servers to disconnect the other user.  This fake user will\n remain online for NickServ to ensure that the other\n user does not immediately reconnect; after that time, you\n can reclaim your nick.  Alternatively, use the RELEASE\n command (/msg NickServ HELP RELEASE) to get the nick\n back sooner.\n \n In order to use the RECOVER command for a nick, your\n current address as shown in /WHOIS must be on that nick\'s\n access list, you must be identified and in the group of\n that nick, or you must supply the correct password for\n the nickname.[/quote]\n\n[b]RELEASE[/b]\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  RELEASE nickname [password]\n \n Instructs NickServ to remove any hold on your nickname\n caused by automatic kill protection or use of the RECOVER\n command.  This holds lasts for NickServ;\n this command gets rid of them sooner.\n \n In order to use the RELEASE command for a nick, your\n current address as shown in /WHOIS must be on that nick\'s\n access list, you must be identified and in the group of\n that nick, or you must supply the correct password for\n the nickname.[/quote]\n\n[b]GHOST[/b]\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  GHOST nickname [password]\n \n Terminates a \"ghost\" IRC session using your nick.  A\n \"ghost\" session is one which is not actually connected,\n but which the IRC server believes is still online for one\n reason or another.  Typically, this happens if your\n computer crashes or your Internet or modem connection\n goes down while you\'re on IRC.\n \n In order to use the GHOST command for a nick, your\n current address as shown in /WHOIS must be on that nick\'s\n access list, you must be identified and in the group of\n that nick, or you must supply the correct password for\n the nickname.[/quote]\n \n[b]INFO[/b]\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  INFO nickname [ALL]\n \n Displays information about the given nickname, such as\n the nick\'s owner, last seen address and time, and nick\n options. If you are identified for the nick you\'re\n getting information for and ALL is specified, you will\n be shown all the information; regardless of whether\n it\'s hidden or not.[/quote]\n \n[b]LIST[/b]\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  LIST pattern\n \n Lists all registered nicknames which match the given\n pattern, in nick!user@host format.  Nicks with the\n PRIVATE option set will not be displayed.\n \n Examples:\n \n     LIST *!joeuser@foo.com\n         Lists all nicks owned by joeuser@foo.com.\n \n     LIST *Bot*!*@*\n         Lists all registered nicks with Bot in their\n         names (case insensitive).\n \n     LIST *!*@*.bar.org\n         Lists all nicks owned by users in the bar.org\n         domain.[/quote]\n\n[b]ALIST[/b]\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  ALIST [level]\n \n Lists all channels you have access on. Optionally, you can specify\n a level in XOP or ACCESS format. The resulting list will only\n include channels where you have the given level of access.\n\n Examples:\n     ALIST Founder\n         Lists all channels where you have Founder\n         access.\n\n     ALIST AOP\n         Lists all channels where you have AOP\n         access or greater.\n\n     ALIST 10\n         Lists all channels where you have level 10\n         access or greater.\n\n Channels that have the NOEXPIRE option set will be\n prefixed by an exclamation mark.[/quote]\n[b]GLIST[/b]\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  GLIST\n \n Lists all nicks in your group.[/quote]\n[b]STATUS[/b]\n[quote] Syntax: /msg NickServ  STATUS nickname...\n \n Returns whether the user using the given nickname is\n recognized as the owner of the nickname.  The response has\n this format:\n \n     nickname status-code\n \n where nickname is the nickname sent with the command, and\n status-code is one of the following:\n \n     0 - no such user online or nickname not registered\n     1 - user not recognized as nickname\'s owner\n     2 - user recognized as owner via access list only\n     3 - user recognized as owner via password identification\n \n Up to sixteen nicknames may be sent with each command; the\n rest will be ignored. If no nickname is given, your status\n will be returned.[/quote]',70679,'2012-09-11 15:32:34'),(44636,5763,85636,'2012-07-21 21:58:16','[size=3][b][color=#FF0000]Already in Help - Delete after double check[/color][/b][/size]\n\n\n\n[u]NICKNAME REGISTRATION[/u]\n\nRegistering your nickname on Empornium IRC provides a number of benefits. The most notable of these is that registering your nickname prevents other people from using it. Once a user starts using the nickname, they will be asked to â€˜identifyâ€™ to it with a password. If they fail to do so, their nickname will be changed. This helps to stop people posing as you.\n\nOnce you register your nickname, you can be added to the auto voice and op lists in other peopleâ€™s channels. This enables you to be a permanent staff member in channels. You are also entitled to a vhost once you have been registered.\n\nRegistration provides you with many benefits and is completely free.\n\nTo register your nickname on Empornium IRC, you must first be using it. If you are not currently using it, change to it with the command:\n\n[quote]/nick <nickname>[/quote]\n\nFor example:\n\n[quote]/nick CrazyUser[/quote]\n\nOnce you are using the nickname, you may register it in one of two ways. In any client, use the following command:\n\n[quote]/ns register <password> <e-mail>[/quote]\n\nFor example:\n\n[quote]/ns register supersecretpassword crazyuser@hotmail.com[/quote]\n\nFollowing this, you will be sent an e-mail giving you the details required to finish off the registration. Follow the instructions in the e-mail.\n\nEach time you connect and start using the registered, you will be told that â€œThis nick is owned by someone elseâ€. You must â€˜identifyâ€™ to it using the following command:\n\n[quote]/ns identify <password>[/quote]\n\nFor example:\n\n[quote]/ns identify supersecretpassword[/quote]\n\nIf you use mIRC, you can load the following script into the Remotes section of your script editor (press alt+R to access this) to identify you automatically. Just replace â€˜YOURPASSWORDHEREâ€™ with your actual password:\n\non 1:NOTICE:*This nickname is registered and protected*:?: {\n   if ($nick == NickServ) {\n      ns identify YOURPASSWORDHERE\n   }\n}\n\non 1:NOTICE:*This nick is owned by someone else*:?: {\n   if ($nick == NickServ) {\n      ns identify YOURPASSWORDHERE\n   }\n}\n\nIf you require help, come and see us in [url=http://torrents.empornium.me/irc.php]#empornium-help on irc.emprn.tk[/url]. Users who have registered with NickServ will automatically get voiced in the channel when they join.',70679,'2012-09-10 18:07:19'),(44637,5763,85636,'2012-07-21 22:00:43','[size=3][b][color=#FF0000]Moved to staff irc reference - delete after double check[/color][/b][/size]\n\n\n[u]Registering A Channel[/u]\n\n\nRegistering your channel on Empornium IRC gives you many advantages, and is completely free. These include:\n\nIncreased control over your channel\nAbility to add people to the auto op list\nAbility to add auto kicks\nAbility to use a services bot to auto moderate your channel\nAnd many many moreâ€¦\nTo register your channel, you must first register your nickname. To do this, when you are using the nickname that you wish to register, type the following command into your IRC client:\n\n[quote]/ns register password e-mail[/quote]\n\nYou must replace password and e-mail with a real password and e-mail address, respectively. An example of the use of this command is:\n\n[quote]/ns register supersecretpassword fred@hotmail.com[/quote]\n\nIt is important that you use your real e-mail address as this will be used in future if you ever forget your password. We will not send any unsolicited e-mail to this address.\n\nOnce you have registered your nickname, you can register your channel. All channels names begin with the # symbol, for example #help, #chris and #247fixes. Once you have picked a channel name, you can join it using the command:\n\n[quote]/join #channel[/quote]\n\nFor example:\n\n[quote]/join #chat[/quote]\n\nOnce you have joined the channel, if it is not already registered, you should see your name in the nickname list with the @ symbol next to it. This means you are an operator in the channel. You may now register it with the following command:\n\n[quote]/cs register #channel password description[/quote]\n\nYou must replace #channel, password and description with the channel name, the channel password and a description of the channel. An example of the use of this command is:\n\n[quote]/cs register #chat verysecretpassword Freds chat channel[/quote]\n\nOnce you have done that, you should see your name in the nick list prefixed with the ~ symbol. This means you are the owner of the channel.\n\nIf you have any problems registering your channel, come and talk to us in #empornium-help on irc.emprn.tk\n',70679,'2012-09-11 19:11:22'),(44638,5757,47234,'2012-07-21 22:02:52','Blame me and Lanz lol.  He suggested it would fit into the connectable article great so i cut and pasted it.  Then like a smart clown nuked the old article\r\n\r\nHehe if you checked Emp.me and the empforums chat logs you would have known what we had been up to on that one and would have known who to blame already\n\nSafe bet for future too is if the articles are broken you can blame some clown.  I always seem to break them',47234,'2012-07-21 22:18:48'),(44639,5763,85636,'2012-07-21 22:12:33','[size=3][b][color=#FF0000]Moved to Staff Help - Delete after double check[/color][/b][/size]\n\n\n[b]BOT COMMANDS[/b]\n\nFantasy commands allows you to use simple shortcuts in place of many of the NickServ, ChanServ, and BotServ commands. \n\nThe available commands are listed below; to use them, just type the command indicated (for instance, For more information on a specific command, type !help command.) \n\nThe Fantasy commands are arranged in xxx areas:\nGeneral Commands â€“ General commands available. No special access required.\nAccess Control Commands â€“ Commands to manipulate channel access and levels list(s).\nChannel Settings Commands â€“ Commands to configure the channelsâ€™ settings and lists.\nChannel Action Commands â€“ Commands that will make services perform certain actions.\nChannel Modes Commands â€“ Commands that set certain channel modes.\n\nUsing Fantasy Commands\nTo use Fantasy commands, you first have to turn on the option, using this command:\n/msg botserv set #channel fantasy on\nFor instance, if I wanted to turn on Fantasy commands in #topgear, Iâ€™d use this command:\n/bs set #topgear fantasy on\nOnce Fantasy commands are turned on, you can use any of the commands below, as long as you have the proper access. In other words, you cannot kick someone if youâ€™re not a hop or op on the channel.\n\n[b]General Commands[/b]\n \n!HELP\n Syntax: !HELP\n \n Help for BotServ fantasy commands\n \n!CMDLIST\n Syntax: !CMDLIST\n \n  A list of all available fantasy commands\n \n!IRCOPS\n Syntax: !IRCOPS\n \n  Shows a list of all available global IRCops in the Status Window\n \n!STAFF\n Syntax: !STAFF\n \n  Shows a list of all available global IRCops in the Status Window\n \n!MINFO\n Syntax: !MINFO\n \n Shows information about the module providing the brunt \n of the fantasy commands.\n \n!SVERSION\n Syntax: !SVERSION\n \n Shows information about the Anope IRC Services version \n and build.\n \n!INFO\n Syntax: !INFO [ALL]\n \n  Shows information about the channel. \n The \'all\' option is limited to founders and Services Admins.\n \n[b]Access Control Commands[/b]\n\n!SOP\n Syntax: !SOP add nick\n         !SOP del {nick | entry-num | list}\n         !SOP list [mask | list]\n         !SOP clear\n \n Maintains the SOP (SuperOP) list for the channel.\n The SOP list gives users all rights given by the AOP list, and adds\n those needed to use the AutoKick and the BadWords lists,\n to send and read channel memos, and so on.\n  \n This command may have been disabled for your channel, and\n in that case you need to use the access list. See HELP ACCESS\n for information about the access list, and HELP SET XOP to know how\n to toggle between the access list and xOP list systems.\n \n!AOP\n Syntax: !AOP add nick\n         !AOP del {nick | entry-num | list}\n         !AOP list [mask | list]\n         !AOP clear\n \n Maintains the AOP (AutoOP) list for the channel.\n The AOP list gives users the right to be auto-opped on your channel,\n to unban or invite themselves if needed, to have their\n greet message showed on join, and so on.\n  \n This command may have been disabled for your channel, and\n in that case you need to use the access list. See HELP ACCESS\n for information about the access list, and HELP SET XOP to know how\n to toggle between the access list and xOP list systems.\n \n!HOP\n Syntax: !HOP add nick\n         !HOP del {nick | entry-num | list}\n         !HOP list [mask | list]\n         !HOP clear\n \n Maintains the HOP (HalfOP) list for the channel. The HOP\n list gives users the right to be auto-halfopped on your channel\n \n This command may have been disabled for your channel, and\n in that case you need to use the access list. See HELP ACCESS\n for information about the access list, and HELP SET XOP to know how\n to toggle between the access list and xOP list systems.\n \n Provides access to the HOP (HalfOP) list.\n \n!VOP\n Syntax: !VOP add nick\n         !VOP del {nick | entry-num | list}\n         !VOP list [mask | list]\n         !VOP clear\n \n Maintains the VOP (VOicePeople) list for a channel.\n The VOP list allows users to be auto-voiced and to voice\n themselves if they aren\'t.\n  \n This command may have been disabled for your channel, and\n in that case you need to use the access list. See HELP ACCESS\n for information about the access list, and HELP SET XOP to know how\n to toggle between the access list and xOP list systems.\n \n!ACCESS\n Syntax: !ACCESS add nick level\n         !ACCESS del {nick | entry-num | list}\n         !ACCESS list [mask | list]\n         !ACCESS clear\n \n Maintains the access list for a channel.  The access\n list specifies which users are allowed chanop status or\n access to commands on the channel.\n \n Different user levels allow for access to different subsets of\n privileges; cf. /msg ChanServ HELP ACCESS LEVELS for more specific \n information. Any nick not on the access list has a user level of 0.\n \n!LEVELS\n Syntax: !LEVELS set type level\n         !LEVELS {dis | disable} type\n         !LEVELS list\n         !LEVELS reset\n \n The LEVELS command allows fine control over the meaning of\n the numeric access levels used for the channel.  With this command,\n you can define the access level required for most administrative functions.\n (The SET FOUNDER and SET PASSWORD commands, as well as this command, \n are always restricted to the channel founder.) \n \n LEVELS SET allows the access level for a function or group of \n functions to be changed.\n \n LEVELS DISABLE (or DIS for short) disables an automatic\n feature or disallows access to a function by anyone other \n than the channel founder.\n \n LEVELS LIST shows the current levels for each function or group\n  of functions.\n \n LEVELS RESET resets the levels to the default levels of a \n newly-created channel.\n \n (See /msg ChanServ HELP ACCESS LEVELS for more info.)\n \n For a list of the features and functions whose levels can be\n set, see HELP LEVELS DESC.\n \n[b]Channel Setting Commands[/b]\n\n!AKICK\n Syntax: !AKICK add {mask | user} [reason]\n         !AKICK {stick | unstick | del} mask\n         !AKICK {list | view} [mask]\n         !AKICK {enforce | clear}\n \n Maintains the channel AKICK list. See the ChanServ AKICK command for more details.\n \n!BADWORDS\n Syntax: !BADWORDS add word [single | start | end | any]\n         !BADWORDS del {word | entry-num | list}\n         !BADWORDS list [mask | list]\n         !BADWORDS clear\n \n  Maintains the badwords list. See the  BotServ BADWORDS command  for more details.\n \n!SET\n Syntax: !SET option parameters\n \n Changes channel\'s settings. \n   \n Available options:\n See the ChanServ SET command for more details on the following:\n   founder       -  Set the founder of a channel\n   successor     -  Set the successor for a channel\n   desc          -  Set the channel description\n   url           -  Associate a URL with the channel\n   email         -  Associate an E-mail address with the channel\n   entrymsg      -  Set a message to be sent to users when they enter the \n                    channel\n   bantype       -  Set how Services make bans on the channel\n   mlock         -  Lock channel modes on or off\n   keeptopic     -  Retain topic when channel is not in use\n   topiclock     -  Topic can only be changed with TOPIC\n   opnotice      -  Send a notice when OP/DEOP commands are used\n   peace         -  Regulate the use of critical commands\n   private       -  Hide channel from LIST command\n   restricted    -  restrict access to the channel\n   secure        -  activate services\' security features\n   secureops     -  stricter control of chanop status\n   securefounder -  stricter control of channel founder status\n   signkick      -  Sign kicks that are done with KICK command\n   xop           -  Toggle the user privilege system\n \n \n See the BotServ SET command for more details on the following:\n   noexpire      -  Sets whether the given channel will expire. \n                    (limited to SA)\n   dontkickops   -  Protect channel ops against kicks by the services bot.\n   dontkickvoices - Protect voices against kicks by the services bot.\n   greet         -  Enable greet messages on join.\n   fantasy       -  Enable fantasy commands on the channel.\n   symbiosis     -  Allow the bot to act as a real bot.\n   nobot         -  Prevents a bot from being assigned to this channel. \n                    (limited to SA)\n    \n!BKICK\n Syntax: !BKICK option {on | off} [ttb [params]]\n \n See the BotServ SET command for more details on the following options:\n \n   bolds       -  Sets whether the bot kicks bolds.\n   badwords    -  Sets whether the bots kicks for words in  \n                  the badwords list.\n   caps        -  Sets whether the bot kicks for CAPS.\n   colors      -  Sets whether the bot kicks for colors.\n   flood       -  Sets whether the bot kicks for floods.\n   repeat      -  Sets whether the bot kicks for repeats.\n   reverses    -  Sets whether the bot kicks for reverses.\n   underlines  -  Sets whether the bot kicks for underlines.\n  \n ttb is the number of times a user can be kicked before he gets banned.\n Don\'t give ttb to disable the ban system once activated.\n\n[b]Channel Action Commands[/b]\n\n!CLEAR\n Syntax: !CLEAR {modes | bans | excepts | invites | ops | hops | voices | users}\n \n Clears the specified option on the channel. \n See the ChanServ CLEAR command for more details.\n \n!TOPIC\n Syntax: !TOPIC [topic]\n         !CTOPIC\n Sets the channel topic. If no topic is given, the current \n topic is displayed in the channel.\n \n The CTOPIC command clears the topic.\n \n This command is most useful in conjunction with SET TOPICLOCK \n \n See the ChanServ TOPIC command for more details.\n \n!TAPPEND\n Syntax: {!TAPPEND  | !APPENDTOPIC}  text to be appended to topic\n \n Appends the given text to the channel\'s current topic.\n This command is most useful in conjunction with SET TOPICLOCK \n \n!INVITE\n Syntax: !INVITE\n \n  Invites \'nick\' to the channel if the user is present on the network.\n \n!UP\n Syntax: !UP\n \n Gives the user the modes he has rights to. This will unset modes if he has any\n the user has no access to.\n \n Note: A nick can only be specified by the founder of the channel or \n a Services Root Administrator.\n \n!DOWN\n Syntax: !DOWN [nick] [level]\n \n Unsets all modes. If the channel is moderated, it will reset voice,\n unless issued on another user by a founder. It is also possible\n to specify a target level. \n\n The target level can be any one of the following:\n \n    - q - Channel founder (modes +qo) (IRCd Dependant)\n    - a - Protected Operator / Administrator (modes +ao) (IRCd Dependant)\n    - o - Channel Operator (mode +o)\n    - h - Channel Halfop (mode +h) (IRCd Dependant)\n    - v - \\\"Voice\\\" (mode +v)\n \n If a target level is specified, the users\' current privileges will be  \n replaced by the target one.\n  \n Note: A nick can only be specified by the founder of the channel or \n a Services Root Administrator.\n \n!KICK\n Syntax: !KICK [nick [reason]]\n \n Kick a user from the channel.\n See the ChanServ KICK command for more details.\n \n!KB\n Syntax: {!KICKBAN | !KB} [nick!]ident@host] [reason]\n \n This will kick and ban the specified user or all users matching the given \n mask from the channel. If a mask is given and someone who should not be \n kicked according to the channels\' settings matches it, the command is \n aborted before anyone is kicked or banned.\n \n!TKB\n Syntax: !tkb or !tkban [nick | [nick!]ident@host] [time] [reason]\n \n This will kick and temporarily ban the specified user or all users matching\n the given mask from the channel for the specified amount of time. \n \n If a mask is given and someone who should not be banned according to the\n channels\' settings matches it, the command is aborted before anyone is \n kicked.\n \n Also be aware that this command may not work with IPs for privacy reasons.\n\n If the time is not given or is invalid, it will default to 1 hour.\n The time should be given in the format <(s)/m/h/d>.\n \n Example: !tkb SillyTroll 10m Bye \n This command will kickban the user SillyTroll for 10 minutes.\n \n Note: if Services are restarted before the ban expires, the ban will\n not be automatically removed.\n \n[b]Channel Modes Commands[/b]\n\n!BAN\n Syntax: !BAN [nick | mask]\n \n Bans (a) user(s)/mask from the channel without kicking.\n \n!TBAN\n Syntax: {!TB | !TBAN} [nick | [nick!]ident@host] [time]\n \n This will ban the given nick or hostmask from the channel for the specified\n amount of time. If the time is not given, it will default to 1 hour.\n The time should be given in the format <(s)/m/h/d>.\n \n Example: !tb SillyTroll 10m \n This command will kickban the user SillyTroll for 10 minutes.\n \n Note: if services are restarted before the ban expires, the ban will\n not be automatically removed\n\n!UNBAN\n Syntax: !UNBAN [nick | [nick!]ident@host]\n \n  Removes the ban on a user.\n \n!MUTE\n Syntax: !MUTE  [nick | mask]\n \n Bans or mutes the given nickname or usermask from the channel.  \n See the Silencing Users with Extended Bans for more details.\n \n!UNMUTE\n Syntax: !UNMUTE  [nick | mask]\n \n Unbans or unmutes the given nickname or usermask from the channel.  \n See the Silencing Users with Extended Bans for more details.\n \n!OP\n Syntax: !OP  [nick]\n \n Op yourself or another user.  See the ChanServ  OP command \n for more details.\n \n!DEOP\n Syntax: !DEOP  [nick]\n \n Deop yourself or another user.  See the ChanServ OP command \n for more details.\n \n!VOICE\n Syntax: !VOICE [nick]\n \n Voice yourself or another user. See the ChanServ VOICE command \n for more details.\n \n!DEVOICE\n Syntax: !DEVOICE [nick]\n \n Devoice yourself or another user. See the ChanServ DEVOICE command \n for more details.\n \n!PROTECT\n Syntax: !PROTECT [nick]\n \n Protect yourself or another user (so you cannot be kicked). See \n the ChanServ PROTECT command for more details.\n \n!DEPROTECT\n Syntax: !DEPROTECT [nick]\n \n Remove protection from  yourself or another user. See the \n ChanServ DEPROTECT command for more details.\n \n!OWNER\n Syntax: !OWNER\n \n Give yourself the owner mode. See the ChanServ OWNER command \n for more details.\n\n \n!DEOWNER\n Syntax: !DEOWNER\n \n Remove the owner mode. See the ChanServ DEOWNER command for \n more details.\n \n!HALFOP\n Syntax: !HALFOP [nick]\n \n Halfop yourself or another user. See the ChanServ HALFOP command \n for more details.\n \n!DEHALFOP\n Syntax: !DEHALFOP [nick]\n \n Dehalfop yourself or another user. See the ChanServ DEHALFOP command \n for more details.',70679,'2012-09-10 18:07:46'),(44640,5763,85636,'2012-07-21 22:33:13','[size=3][b][color=#FF0000]Moved to Staff Help - Delete after double check[/color][/b][/size]\n\n\n\nDifferent Lines (For IRC Operators Use Only)\n\n[b][u]KLine[/u][/b]\n\n[quote]Syntax: /KLINE [+|-]user@host | nick [time] <reason>\n \n  Example: /KLINE *@127.0.0.1 2d Abuse\n \n Bans the hostmask from the server it is issued on. A\n kline is not a global ban.   time to ban is\n either: a) a value in seconds, b) a time value, like\n \'1d\' is 1 day or c) \'0\' for permanent.  Time and reason\n are optional, if unspecified a ban time of 7 days and \'no reason\' are used.  \n To remove a kline use /kline -user@host[/quote]\n\n[b][u]GLine[/u][/b]\n\n[quote]Syntax: /GLINE [+|-]user@host | nick [time] <reason>\n\n  Example: /GLINE *@127.0.0.1 2d Abuse \n\n Adds a global ban to anyone that matches. See kline for\n more syntax info.      \n Use /gline -user@host to remove.[/quote]\n\n[b][u]ZLine[/u][/b]\n\n[quote]Syntax: /ZLINE [+|-]*@ip [time] <reason>\n\n Example: /ZLINE *@127.0.0.1 2d Abuse\n \n Bans an IP Address from the local server it is issued\n on (not global). See kline for more syntax info.  \n Use /zline -*@ip to remove.[/quote]\n\n[b][u]GZLine[/u][/b]\n\n[quote]Syntax: /GZLINE [+|-]*@ip [time] <reason>\n\n Example: /GZLINE *@127.0.0.1 2d Abuse\n \n Bans an IP Address from connecting to any server on the network.\n See kline for more syntax info.   \n Use /zline -*@ip to remove.[/quote]',70679,'2012-09-10 21:34:58'),(44641,5763,85636,'2012-07-21 22:44:08','[size=3][b][color=#FF0000]Moved to staff irc reference - delete after double check[/color][/b][/size]\n\n\n[size=2][b][u]Channel Modes[/u][/b][/size]\n\nThis section lists all of the possible channel modes that may be used with /MODE\n\nAn example of the use of this command is: /mode #chills +o Brigitte\n\n[b][u]Mode[/u][/b]\na = Gives Channel Admin to the user\nA = Server/Network Admin only channel (settable by Admins)\nb = Bans the nick!ident@host from the channel.\n       Extended bantypes are also available. (for more info see [url=http://empornium.mooo.com/forums.php?action=viewthread&threadid=2763&page=1#post24642]Extended Bans Tutorial[/url]) [h]\nc = Block messages containing mIRC color codes [o]\nC = No CTCPs allowed in the channel [o]\ne = Overrides a ban for matching users [h]\nf = Flood protection (for more info see [url=http://empornium.mooo.com/forums.php?action=viewthread&threadid=2763&page=1#post24643]channel flood protection tutorial[/url]) [o]\nG = Filters out all Bad words in messages with [o]\nh = Gives HalfOp status to the user (Limited Channel operator access)\ni = A user must be invited to join the channel [h]\nI = Overrides +i for matching users [h]\nj = Throttle joins per-user to â€˜joinsâ€™ per â€˜secâ€™ seconds [o]\nk = Users must specify to join (for more info see [url=http://empornium.mooo.com/forums.php?action=viewthread&threadid=2763&page=1#post24644]Using Channel Keys[/url]) [h]\nK = /KNOCK is not allowed [o]\nl = Channel may hold at most of users [o]\nL = Channel link (If +l is full, the next user will auto-join ) [q]\nm = Moderated channel (only +vhoaq users may speak) [h]\nM = Must be using a registered nick (+r), or have voice access to talk [o]\nn = Users outside the channel can not send PRIVMSGs to the channel [h]\nN = No Nickname changes are permitted in the channel [o]\no = Gives Channel Operator status to the user\nO = IRC Server Operator only channel (settable by IRCops)\np = Private channel (for more info see Using Channel Modes to [url=http://empornium.mooo.com/forums.php?action=viewthread&threadid=2763&page=1#post24645]Hide Your Channel[/url]) [o]\nq = Gives Owner status to the user\nQ = No kicks allowed [o]\nr = The channel is registered (settable by services only)\nR = Only registered (+r) users may join the channel [o]\ns = Secret channel (for more info see Using Channel Modes to [url=http://empornium.mooo.com/forums.php?action=viewthread&threadid=2763&page=1#post24645]Hide Your Channel[/url]) [o] \nS = Strips mIRC color codes [o]\nt = Only +hoaq may change the topic [h]\nT = No NOTICEs allowed in the channel [o]\nu = Auditorium mode (/names and /who #channel only show channel ops) [q]\nU = Block messages containing mIRC formatting codes [o]\nv = Gives Voice to the user (May talk if chan is +m)\nV = /INVITE is not allowed [o]\nz = Only Clients on a Secure Connection (SSL) can join [o]\n\n[size=2][u][b]Key[/b][/u][/size]\n[h] requires at least halfop\n[o] requires at least chanop\n[q] requires owner\n\n\n[b][u]User Modes[/u][/b]\n\n\nHere is a list of all the user modes which are available for use. An example command for setting a mode on yourself is: /umode +D\n\n[b][u]Modes[/u][/b]\n\na = Is a Services Administrator [o]\nA = Is a Server Administrator [o]\nB = Marks you as being a Bot <u>\nC = Is a Co Administrator [o]\nd = Makes it so you can not receive channel PRIVMSGs (Deaf)\nD = Makes it so you cannot receive private PRIVMSGs (Deaf to PMs)\ng = Can read & send to GlobOps, and LocOps [o]\nG = Filters out all Bad words in your messages with <censored> <u>\nh = Available for Help [h & o]\nH = Hide IRCop status in /WHO and /WHOIS. [o]\ni = Invisible (Not shown in /WHO searches) [Cannot be removed for security reasons]\nN = Is a Network Administrator (IRC Operators only)\no = Global IRC Operator (IRC Operators only)\nO = Local IRC Operator (IRC Operators only)\np = Hide all channels in /whois and /who\nq = Only U:lines can kick you (Services Admins/Net Admins only)\nr = Identifies the nick as being Registered (settable by services only)\nR = Allows you to only receive PRIVMSGs/NOTICEs from registered (+r) users\ns = Can listen to Server notices [Cannot be set  for security reasons]\nS = For Services only. (Protects them) [Cannot be set to any user or oper]\nt = Says that you are using a /VHOST [Cannot be set except by services]\nT = Prevents you from receiving CTCPs\nv = Receive infected DCC send rejection notices\nV = Marks the client as a WebTV user\nw = Can listen to Wallop messages\nW = Lets you see when people do a /WHOIS on you [o]\nx = Gives the user a hidden hostname (security)\nz = Marks the client as being on a Secure Connection (SSL) [Can only be set by connecting to port 6697]\n\n[b][u]Key[/u][/b]\n\n[h] requires being operator in the network help channel\n[o] Can only be set by operator\n<u> Can be set by any user',70679,'2012-09-11 19:41:11'),(44642,5763,85636,'2012-07-21 22:45:12','[size=3][b][color=#FF0000]Moved to Staff Help - Delete after double check[/color][/b][/size]\n\n\n[b][u]Extended Ban\'s[/u][/b] \n\n[b]Silencing Users with Extended Bans[/b]\nYou can use extended bans to set up an alternative kind of ban that will give you more options, like silencing users.\n\nWhen you silence a user, you allow the person to stay in the channel, but block the personâ€™s ability to participate in the discussion or change nicks. Itâ€™s an online equivalent of a short timeout, where the person has to sit quietly for several minutes before rejoining discussion.\n\nTo silence a user manually, youâ€™d type:\n\n[quote]/mode #YourChannel +bb ~q:nick!ident@user.host ~n:nick!ident@user.host[/quote]\nThat command sets two bans, which is why the host information is listed twice. The first one (~q:nick!ident@user.host) prevents the user from participating in the discussion (unless the user is +v or higher). The ~q stands for quiet. The second one (~n: nick!ident user.host) prevents the user from changing nicks. The ~n stands for nick.\n\nIn #YourChannel, bans are normally set by the userâ€™s host, so an example ban would look like this:\n\n[quote]/mode #YourChannel +bb ~n:*!*@protectedhost-1234578.hsd1.va.comcast.net ~q:*!*@protectedhost-1234578.hsd1.va.comcast.net[/quote]\nThat example bans anyone (with any nick or ident) with the hostmask protectedhost-12345678.hsd1.va.comcast.net.\n\n \n[b]Removing a Silence Extended Ban[/b]\nIf you silence a user manually, you have to remove the ban manually as well. Since you set the ban with +b, you will remove it by using the same command, but with -b. So to remove the ban, you would type:\n\n[quote]/mode #YourChannel -bb ~q:nick!ident@user.host ~n:nick!ident@user.host[/quote]\nEverything is the same. Youâ€™re just removing the ban. Hereâ€™s the way to remove the example ban from above:\n\n[quote]/mode #YourChannel -bb ~n:*!*@protectedhost-1234578.hsd1.va.comcast.net ~q:*!*@protectedhost-1234578.hsd1.va.comcast.net[/quote]\n \n[b]Setting a Channel Extended Ban[/b]\nThere are two other kinds of extended bans:\n\n~c sets an extended ban based on a channel users are in\n~r sets an extended ban based on a userâ€™s real name\nYou are unlikely to need either of these bans, but for the sake of thoroughness here is how they work.\n\nTo set an extended channel ban, youâ€™d type:\n\n[quote]/mode #YourChannel +b ~c:#channel[/quote]\nThat ban would prevent anyone in #channel from joining #YourChannel.\n\nLetâ€™s pretend thereâ€™s a channel called #YourChannelHaters. We might decide that we do not want anyone from #YourChannelHaters to join #YourChannel. We could use this extended ban to prevent them from joining #YourChannel:\n\n[quote]/mode #YourChannel +b ~c:#YourChannelHaters[/quote]\nYou remove this kind of ban by switching to -b, so I could remove the ban on folks from #YourChannelHaters like this:\n\n[quote]/mode #YourChannel -b ~c:#YourChannelHaters[/quote]\n \n[b]Setting a Real Name Extended Ban[/b]\nTo set an extended ban based on a userâ€™s real name, youâ€™d type:\n\n[quote]/mode #YourChannel +b ~r:*real_name*[/quote]\nThe * character works as a wildcard, just as it does in other bans. Use the underscore character ( _ ) to represent spaces in the userâ€™s real name. The underscore is also interpreted as an actual underscore character. In other words, the ban above would block someone using either â€œreal nameâ€ (with a space) or â€œreal_nameâ€ (with an underscore).\n\nHereâ€™s an example: \n\n[quote]/mode #YourChannel +b ~r:*Jane_Doe*[/quote]\nThat ban would prevent anyone who was using the real name â€œJane Doeâ€ or â€œJane_Doeâ€ from joining #YourChannel. Because of the * wildcard, someone with a real name like â€œJane Doe rulesâ€ or â€œJane_Doe_rulesâ€ would also be banned.\n\nYou remove this kind of ban by switching to -b, so I could remove the ban on â€œJane Doe â€ like this:\n\n[quote]/mode #YourChannel -b ~r:*Jane_Doe*[/quote]',70679,'2012-09-10 21:42:11'),(44643,5763,85636,'2012-07-21 22:52:07','[size=3][b][color=#FF0000]Moved to staff irc reference - delete after double check[/color][/b][/size]\n\n\n[b][u]Channel Flood Protection[/u][/b]\n\nThe +f channel mode provides comprehensive flood protection for a channel. This mode allows you to prevent join, nick change, CTCP, text, and knock floods. The syntax for this modeâ€™s parameter is as follows:\n\n[quote]/mode #channel +f [{#}{,...}]:[/quote]\n\nThe amount specifies the number of times the specified flood must occur before action is taken. \n\nBelow are the available types:\n\n[table]\n[tr]\n[td] Type [/td][td] Name [/td][td] Default Action [/td][td] Other Actions [/td]\n[/tr]\n[tr]\n[td] c [/td][td] CTCP [/td][td] +C (no channel CTCPs allowed) [/td][td] +m (only voiced users can speak), +M (only registered users can speak) [/td]\n[/tr]\n[tr]\n[td] j [/td][td] Join [/td][td] +i (invite only) [/td][td] R (only registered users can join) [/td]\n[/tr]\n[tr]\n[td] k [/td][td] Knock [/td][td] +K (no knocks allowed) [/td][td] None [/td]\n[/tr]\n[tr]\n[td] m [/td][td] Message [/td][td] +m (only voiced users can speak) [/td][td] +M (only registered users can speak) [/td]\n[/tr]\n[tr]\n[td] n [/td][td] Nickname Change [/td][td] +N (no nickname changes allowed) [/td][td] None [/td]\n[/tr]\n[tr]\n[td] t [/td][td] text [/td][td] User is kicked from the channel [/td][td] +b (user is banned from the channel) [/td]\n[/tr]\n[/table]\n\nN.B. The difference between type [b]m[/b] and [b]t[/b] is that [b]m[/b] is tallied for the entire channel whereas [b]t[/b] is tallied per user.\n\nIf you choose to specify an action for a mode, you may also specify a time (in minutes) after which the specific action will be reversed.\n\nAn example of the use of this command is:\n\n[quote]/mode #chills +f [2c#C5,6j#R3,3k#K10,15m#m5,5n#N3,5t#b60]:5[/quote]\n\nThis meansâ€¦\n\nIf there are 2 channel CTCP messages (2c) in 5 seconds(:5) set mode +C for 5 mins (#C5)\nIf there are 6 joins (6j) in 5 seconds (:5) set mode +R for 3 mins (#R3)\nIf there are 3 /KNOCK commands on the channel (3k) in 5 seconds (:5) set mode +K for 10 mins (#K10)\nIf there are 15 messages in total from all users (15m) in 5 seconds (:5) set mode +m for 5 mins (#m5)\nIf there are 5 nickname changes (n5) in 5 seconds (:5) set mode +N for 3 mins (#N3)\nIf there are 5 messages from any single user (5t) in 5 seconds (:5) ban the user for 60 mins (#b60)\n\n\nIt has been observed lately that bot nets are joining channels and rapidly joining and parting. In order to prevent this, you can use channel mode [b]j[/b]. This mode will allow only x joins to your channel in y seconds for each client. The recommended setting for this is 1 join in 1 second as this will entirely eradicate join/part flooding from botnets. An example of the use of this is:\n\n[quote]/mode #chills +j 1:1[/quote]\n\nIf you need any help, come and see us in #empornium-help on irc.emprn.tk',70679,'2012-09-11 19:55:43'),(44644,5763,85636,'2012-07-21 22:58:56','[size=3][b][color=#FF0000]Moved to staff irc reference - delete after double check[/color][/b][/size]\n\n\n\n[b][u]Channel Passwords[/u][/b]\n\n\nIf you ever had a secret password to get into your clubhouse, you understand the way that channel keys work. You can set a channel key for your channel, and only those people who have the key will be able to join the channel. If you want to have private conversations, using a channel key is a simple way to make it happen.\n\n[b][u]Setting a Channel Key[/u][/b]\n\nTo set a channel key, use this command:\n\n[quote]/mode #channel +k channelkey[/quote] \n\nIn that command, replace \"channel\" with your #channel and replace \"channelkey\" with your channel key (your password). For instance, for my super-secret channel, I used this command:\n\n[quote]/mode #baconmylove +k nomnomnom [/quote] \n\nWhen you set a channel key, everyone in the channel will see the new key. When I set my channel key, for instance, the server announced this in the channel:\n\n * MrRandom sets mode: +k nomnomnom\n\n[b][u]TIPS[/u][/b]\n\nBe sure that you choose a strong password that others will not easily guess. \n\nMake sure you remove anyone you do not want to have the key before you set it. You can ask him to leave OR kick and ban if necessary. Remember that the server announces the key in channel when you set it, so everyone in your channel will see the new key.\n\nAnyone who has half-op status or higher in your channel can change the channel key. If you cannot trust someone, donâ€™t make that person a moderator. He could easily change the password and lock everyone out of the channel! This can be fixed by doing [quote]/cs clear #channel modes[/quote]\n\nThe channel key will only remain as long as someone is in the channel. If everyone leaves, the next person who joins will be able to do so without knowing the channel key. The easiest solution to this problem is either to add a bnc user to the channel or create a private bot to occupy the channel. Note that services bots will not hold a channel open.\n\n\n[u][b]Joining a Channel with a Key[/b][/u]\n\nYou need to provide the password to join your channel now once you set your key. Hereâ€™s how to use the JOIN command with a channel key:\n\n[quote]/join #channel password[/quote]\n\nFor my super-secret channel, I used this command:\n\n[quote]/join #baconmylove nomnomnom[/quote]\n\nYouâ€™ll need to give your password and this command to everyone who you want to grant access to your channel. Only give your channel password to the people you trust with access to your private space.\n\n[b][u]Changing your Channel Key[/u][/b]\n\nTo change your channel key, just use the same command with a new password:\n\n/mode #channel +k newchannelkey \nThe command is exactly the same. You just indicate the new channel key when you use the command.\n\n[b][u]Troubleshooting[/u][/b]\n\nYou see this error message in your status window: #channel :Cannot join channel (+k)\nEither you didnâ€™t include the password or you used the wrong password. Check with the channel owner for the correct password or to ask for access to the channel.\n\nYou get locked out of your own channel.\nIf you forget your password or someone else changes it, you can just change your channel key and join with the new key. If a moderator in your channel changed the password without your permission, you may want to talk to that person or remove his access. Remember you should only add people as half-ops, ops, or admins if you trust them completely.\n\nIf you are an owner who gets locked out of your channel join the network help channel #silentzombies-help @ irc.emprn.tk they will help you get your channel back.',70679,'2012-09-11 19:27:27'),(44645,5763,85636,'2012-07-21 23:03:40','[size=3][b][color=#FF0000]Moved as is to to staff operator reference - Delete after double check[/color][/b][/size]\n\n\n[b]Hide your Channel[/b]\n\n[b]Secret vs. Private[/b]\n\nThere are two modes you can use to hide your channel: [b]+s[/b], for a secret channel; and [b]+p[/b], for a private channel.\n\nOriginally (that is, in earlier days of IRC), there was a difference between these two modes. On Empornium IRC, the two commands do the same thing. If you set your channel to [b]+p[/b] or to [b]+s[/b], your channel will not show up in the channel listing that someone gets after using the /LIST command and in a /WHOIS list for a user who is in the channel (unless the person using the command is also in the secret channel)\n\nSince the two commands do the same thing, you can only set one or the other.\n\n[b]Setting the Secret or Private Mode[/b]\n\nTo set the secret mode, use this command:\n\n[quote]/mode #channel +s[/quote]\n\nIn that command, replace \"channel\" with your #channel. For instance, for my super-secret channel, I used this command:\n\n[quote]/mode #baconmylove +s[/quote] \n\nTo set the private mode, use this command:\n\n[quote]/mode #channel +p[/quote]\n\nFor instance, I used this command:\n\n[quote]/mode #baconmylove +p[/quote]\n  \n[b]Restrictions on the +s and +p Modes[/b]\n\nIf you set your channel to +s and then decide to set +p, the server will respond by removing the +s setting. Youâ€™d see something like this:\n\n[quote]* MrRandom sets mode: +s\n* MrRandom sets mode: +p-s[/quote]\n\nIn the second line, the server set +p (adding the private setting), and [b]-s[/b] (removing the secret setting). This is normal. Since the commands do the same thing, you only need one or the other (never both). As long as you have the channel set to [b]+s[/b] or to [b]+p[/b], it will be hidden.\n\n[b]Removing the Secret or Private Mode[/b]\n\nIf you no longer want your channel to be hidden, you can remove the secret or private mode easily:\n\nTo remove the secret mode, use this command:\n\n[quote]/mode #channel -s[/quote]\n\nTo remove the private mode, use this command:\n\n[quote]/mode #channel -p[/quote]\n\nOnce you remove the setting, your channel will be visible to everyone on the network.\n\n[b]Two Tips on Using the Secret or Private Mode[/b]\n\nRemember that even though your channel is hidden, the people you ask to join you in the channel can tell others about it. Only invite people to join your channel if you trust them to maintain your privacy. If you cannot trust someone not to tell others about the space, donâ€™t ask them to join your channel.\n\nAny moderator (half-ops, ops, and admins) on your channel can change the channel mode. Donâ€™t add someone as a moderator in the channel if you cannot trust that person to leave the channel with the settings you want.',70679,'2012-09-11 19:22:02'),(44646,5755,86439,'2012-07-21 23:13:24','A possible Help Tute.\n\n\nDont fall into the Hole     OR    Dig yourself out of the Hole    OR     My ratio is fucked, help me     OR      Tips for keeping a good ratio\n\n\nBe aware\n - Choose your torrents carefully.\n\n - Download the entire torrent, DL\'ing less than 100% of all files will prevent that torrent awarding credits.\n\n - Seed, seed everything, never delete it (at least not until its replaced), they help you get credits which can be converted to ratio DL reductions. Thus improving your ratio without having to actually upload a byte. This is not a replacement for ratio, its merely recognition of genuine attempts to seed back where there is a genuine lack of leechers.\n\n - While seed/leecher ratio is a guide to the potential to seed back, be aware that if the torrent has multiple files, and its a few days old, theres a good chance many of those leechers are in essence pseudo seeds now. Many fall into this trap. They will always be listed as leechers due to not completing every last file in that torrent. They never become listed as seeds. Thats not a big deal for them (except as mentioned re: Credits) but it is a big deal for you, they will not DL from you which is what you\'re comparing seed/leecher ratios for in the first place.\n\n - Freeleech, look for fresh (less than a day old) freeleech torrents (gold coin here). And dont DL normal torrents until you have a good ratio buffer.\n\n\nBe patient, and control yourself\n - Never DL an old torrent, no matter how much you want it, until you have a buffer large enough to cover it. You will not seed this back to 1:1 for years, if ever. Once you have that buffer, go for it and enjoy the older stuff and keep it seeding for the benefit of others. Theres a caveat to this concept. Old torrents can be good providers of UL, when youre among the last seeders, often you will be the only one seeding at a particular time, so when uploading you might just gain a good ratio boost on that one torrent late as the other seeders delete it from their client and or HDD. But it generally wont happen in the short term.\n\n - Build a buffer using any or all of the techniques listed here, with an appropriate buffer you never need worry too much about ratio. This is a guessing game to some degree, although you can keep an eye on its progress by watching your ratio. Your buffer should be a reflection of how much you DL each week, and how much you can upload each week. ie: If you like about 20 gig of stuff each month, you would want to upload in excess of that amount. In the early stages this seems limiting, but as the first month or two progresses you will have more torrents seeding, and more credits accumulating. This is the buffer you want, but you need to build it, and building takes some time. I would choose a buffer that was at least double what I want each month. Just keep an eye on it to make sure you dont forget ratio, things do change.\n\n\nIf thats not enough, check out this http://empornium.mooo.com/articles.php?topic=getting_out_of_troub',86439,'2012-07-21 23:48:02'),(44647,5755,129045,'2012-07-21 23:19:12','FLS can edit articles... should I be fixing the minor stuff I pointed out? :hmmm:\r\n\r\nSeems pretty straight forward, but I don\'t want to screw anything :P',129045,'2012-07-21 23:19:45'),(44648,5755,84499,'2012-07-21 23:40:35','\r\n\r\nYes FLS can and should edit articles, minor corrections and stuff I think its okay if you go ahead... Clownius probably has a better idea of what needs doing. Some sections need a more major overhaul and probably need some expert attention. I would say be fairly bold, and if you are unsure you can always post a draft version here or ask in the staff testing forum. \r\n\r\nJust dont press delete instead of edit :D',NULL,NULL),(44649,5757,84499,'2012-07-21 23:46:47','\r\nlol, you expect me to read the chat archive? :D\r\n\r\nIt does make sense for the connchecker information to be in the Connection article though... and will probably be confusing if there is a seperate smaller connchecker article which replicates it :hmmm:  probably I will just hardcode the info on the connchecker page anyway.',NULL,NULL),(44650,5759,84499,'2012-07-21 23:48:18','\r\nlol, ok....\r\n\r\nthanks for the catch :gjob:',NULL,NULL),(44651,5737,115474,'2012-07-22 01:17:13','I also like the big \"Thank the uploader\" button too. I was almost gonna report that as a \"bug\" till I found the poll ;) Off for more bug hunting =p',NULL,NULL),(44652,5763,85636,'2012-07-22 01:28:51','[size=3][b][color=#FF0000]Already in Help - Delete after double check[/color][/b][/size]\n\n\n\n[b][u]Grouping Nicknames[/u][/b]\n\nSo youâ€™ve registered your nick, but have more than one computer/device that you join IRC from. You might be wondering â€œdo I need to register a new nick and have people add that nick to access lists as well? Certainly there must be an easier way.â€\n\nWell luckily for you, there is. You are able to group nicks together so that permissions and other data are shared among accounts. Some of the items that are shared include (but are not limited to): channel ownership, permission levels (owner, halfop, etc.) on channels, group info that was provided when you registered, password, and virtual host. Pretty much anything your single nick has associated with it will be associated with the group of nicks that you have registered.\n\nHereâ€™s how to group a nick to one that you already have registered:\n\n* Switch to the nick that you want to group\n       NOTE 1: Before you enter the next command, make sure that you are using the nick you want to add to your \n       existing group. Do NOT be using your main nick. Example: if I wanted to group JayneCobb to my account, I \n       would /nick JayneCobb.\n       NOTE 2: If you use a registered nick when the next step if performed, it will first be dropped, then \n       grouped to the main nick. Example: if I try to group JayneCobb (which is registered) to my main nick \n       MalcolmReynolds, Services will first drop JayneCobb, then have it join the MalcolmReynolds group. By being \n       dropped, any permissions JayneCobb had will be gone.\n\n* Enter the following command in the server/status window: \n[quote]/msg nickserv group main_nick password[/quote] \n       where main_nick is your primary nick, and password is the password belonging to the primary nick.\n\n[quote]Example: I want to group JayneCobb to my primary nick, MalcolmReynolds, and the password for it is S3reni+yV@ll3y (you do use something secure for your passwords, right?). I would type the following as JayneCobb: /msg nickserv group MalcolmReynolds S3reni+yV@ll3y[/quote]\n\nLook for nickserv to either tell you that you have joined the group of your primay nick or give you an error message, such as â€œyou must wait at least 60 seconds before using the group command againâ€.\n\nAnd just to give you the commands again, they are, in order:\n\n[quote]/nick theNewNick[/quote]\n[quote]/msg nickserv group main_nick password[/quote]\n\nNow what if you want to delink a nick, i.e. remove it from the group, is there some way to do that? Yes there is, you just drop it by switching to the nick, and doing \n[quote]/msg nickserv drop [/quote]\nDoing that will make nickserv completely drop the nick â€“ it will no longer exist, have any permissions, etc.\n\nIs there someway to delink it without dropping, or without it losing the permissions and other information? Not currently, although I suppose it is possible that it could end up in a future version of services, or someone could create a module that could drop a nick and register it using the credentials of the former group and preserving permissions, etc.\n\nShould you have any questions about grouping nicks, feel free to leave a comment here, or to join #empornium-help and ask in there.',70679,'2012-09-10 18:11:37'),(44653,5757,47234,'2012-07-22 01:41:28','Could we link the connectable article to the conn-checker or could i just copy and paste the article back and have it hidden in tutorials on only viable on the conn checker page.  sadly i cant just copy and paste back as i cant remember the url for conn-checker',NULL,NULL),(44654,5679,47234,'2012-07-22 01:44:07','Thrown 10 slots and 100k credits at both PornJacker and Belam to use for testing',47234,'2012-07-22 01:44:19'),(44655,5763,85636,'2012-07-22 01:44:38','[size=3][b][color=#FF0000]Moved as is to to staff operator reference - Delete after double check[/color][/b][/size]\n\n\n\n\n[u][b]IRC Operator Commands[/b][/u]\n\n[b]OPER[/b]\n Syntax: /OPER userid password\n \n Command to give a user operator status if they match an\n Oper Block\n \n[b]WALLOPS[/b]\n Syntax: /WALLOPS message\n \n Sends a message to all users with umode +w\n \n[b]GLOBOPS[/b]\n Syntax: /GLOBOPS message\n \n Sends a message to all global IRCops\n \n[b]CHATOPS[/b]\n Syntax: /CHATOPS message\n \n Sends a message to all IRCops (local and global)\n \n[b]LOCOPS[/b]\n Syntax: /LOCOPS message\n \n Sends a message to all local IRCops\n \n[b]ADCHAT[/b]\n Syntax: /ADCHAT message\n \n Sends a message to all Admins\n \n[b]NACHAT[/b]\n Syntax: /NACHAT message\n \n Sends a message to all Net Admins\n \n[b]KILL[/b]\n Syntax: /KILL nick reason\n \n Kills a user from the network\n \n[b]KLINE[/b]\n Syntax: /KLINE [+|-]user@host | nick [time to ban reason]\n \n Bans the hostmask from the server it is issued on. A\n kline is not a global ban.   time to ban is\n either: a) a value in seconds, b) a time value, like\n \'1d\' is 1 day or c) \'0\' for permanent.  Time and reason\n are optional, if unspecified set::default-bantime\n (default: 0/permanent) and \'no reason\' are used.  To\n remove a kline use /kline -user@host\n \n[b]ZLINE[/b]\n Syntax: /ZLINE [+|-]*@ip [time to ban reason]\n \n Bans an IP Address from the local server it is issued\n on (not global). See kline for more syntax info.   Use\n /zline -*@ip to remove.\n \n[b]GLINE[/b]\n Syntax: /GLINE [+|-]user@host | nick [time to ban reason]\n \n Adds a global ban to anyone that matches. See kline for\n more syntax info.      Use /gline -user@host to remove.\n \n[b]SHUN[/b]\n Syntax: /SHUN [+|-]user@host | nick [time to shun reason]\n \n Prevents a user from executing ANY commands and\n prevents them from speaking. Shuns are global (like\n glines). See kline for more syntax info. Use /shun\n -user@host to remove a shun.\n \n[b]GZLINE[/b]\n Syntax: /GZLINE [+|-]ip time to ban :reason\n \n Adds a global zline. See kline for more syntax info.\n   Use /gzline -*@ip to remove a gzline.\n \n[b]REHASH[/b]\n Syntax: /REHASH server â€“flags\n \n Rehashes the servers config file. Including a server\n name allows you to rehash a remote servers config file.\n Several flags are also available. They Include -motd -\n Only rehash all MOTD and RULES files (including tld {})\n      -opermotd - Only rehash the OPERMOTD file\n -botmotd - Only rehash the BOTMOTD file      -garbage -\n Force garbage collection\n\n[b]SETHOST[/b]\n Syntax: /SETHOST newhost\n \n Lets you change your vhost to what ever you want it to\n be.\n \n[b]SETIDENT[/b]\n Syntax: /SETIDENT newident\n \n Lets you set your ident to what ever you want it to be\n \n[b]CHGHOST[/b]\n Syntax: /CHGHOST nick newhost\n \n Lets you change the host name of a user currently on\n the system\n \n[b]CHGIDENT[/b]\n Syntax: /CHGIDENT nick newident\n \n Lets you change the ident of a user currently on the\n system\n \n[b]CHGNAME[/b]\n Syntax: /CHGNAME nick newname\n \n Lets you change the realname of a user currently on the\n system\n \n[b]SQUIT[/b]\n Syntax: /SQUIT server\n \n Disconnects a server from the network\n DO NOT USE UNLESS YOU KNOW WHAT YOU\'RE DOING\n \n[b]CONNECT[/b]\n Syntax: /CONNECT server port server\n \n If only one server is given, it will attempt to connect\n the server you are ON to the given server. If 2 servers\n are given, it will attempt to connect the 2 servers\n together. Put the leaf server as the first, and the hub\n server as the second.\n \n[b]DCCDENY[/b]\n Syntax: /DCCDENY filemask reason\n \n Adds a DCCDENY for that filemask. Preventing that file\n from being sent.\n \n[b]UNDCCDENY[/b]\n Syntax: /UNDCCDENY filemask\n \n Removes a DCCDENY\n \n[b]RPING[/b]\n Syntax: /RPING servermask\n \n Will calculate in milliseconds the lag between servers\n \n[b]TRACE[/b]\n Syntax: /TRACE servermask|nickname\n \n When used on a user it will give you class and lag\n info. If you use  it on a server it gives you\n class/version/link info.\n \n[b]OPERMOTD[/b]\n Syntax: /OPERMOTD\n \n Displays the servers OperMotd File\n \n[b]ADDMOTD[/b]\n Syntax: /ADDMOTD :text\n \n Will add the given text to the end of the Motd\n \n[b]ADDOMOTD[/b]\n Syntax: /ADDOMOTD :text\n \n Will add the given text to the end of the OperMotd\n \n[b]SDESC[/b]\n Syntax: /SDESC newdescription\n \n Allows server admins to change the description line of\n their server without restarting.\n  \n[b]CLOSE[/b]\n Syntax: /CLOSE\n \n This command will disconnect all unknown connections\n from the IRC server.',70679,'2012-09-11 18:52:00'),(44656,5757,84499,'2012-07-22 01:45:18','\r\nits cool dont worry about it clownius... its a 30 sec cut and paste job if i want to recreate it :wink:',NULL,NULL),(44657,5755,47234,'2012-07-22 01:46:50','Yeah only Clowns delete entire articles and find out later they shouldnt have :lol:\r\n\r\nAnyway a trainer stole my train so im spending an hour now doing some minor fixes on works time :)  Not often i get paid over $70hr to work here',NULL,NULL),(44658,5755,86439,'2012-07-22 01:58:37','Must be your shout then?\n\n\nSomething very odd in this Help Tute http://empornium.mooo.com/articles.php?topic=connectable\n\nThe links re: uTorrent images are not clickable, nor are they highlightable to copy etc.\n\n[URL=http://imgbox.com/abfMIUo7][IMG]http://t.imgbox.com/abfMIUo7.jpg[/IMG][/URL] \n\n[color=blue]Links appear to have lost their picture factor.  Something to do with Freeimage being down maybe.  In any case looking into it and will update links :)[/color]\n\n[color=red]Fixed[/color]\n',47234,'2012-07-22 10:25:39'),(44659,5755,47234,'2012-07-22 02:04:05','Knickers i just realised your FLS so you can edit syntax changes in.  Why is this :clown: doing it',NULL,NULL),(44660,5738,84499,'2012-07-22 02:16:29','\r\n\r\nI made a small change to the view conversation page that hopefully makes it a little clearer what is happening with a staff message.',NULL,NULL),(44661,5755,86439,'2012-07-22 02:31:35','So all that stuff I did re: syntax above, I just change in the Articles? Like, ALL OF IT? Sweet.\n\n\n\nSeriously though, theres still some stuff I wouldnt alter, I dont want to alter anything Im not sure about like LINKS or things like the section on IP\'s for the site as a method of tracking ala Demonoid. Im pretty sure its no longer relevant due to the passkey and whatnot, but still, I could be wrong on that. \n\nText, easy as.\n\n\n\n',86439,'2012-07-22 03:02:49'),(44662,5679,115474,'2012-07-22 02:32:46','I would like to request some extra credits so I can try out the new options that is available in the bonus shop now! :D\r\n\r\nBtw, side question, will the credits we accumulated from the original site eventually transfer over here when this beta goes final or are the credits given here random?',NULL,N